  "prompt": "What are evidence processing laws?",
  "response": "Evidence processing laws are legal guidelines and regulations that govern how physical, digital, and testimonial evidence is collected, handled, preserved, and presented in legal proceedings. These laws are designed to ensure the integrity, reliability, and admissibility of evidence in criminal and civil cases. Key aspects of evidence processing laws include:\n\n1. Chain of custody\n- Documenting who handles evidence\n- Tracking evidence from collection to presentation in court\n- Preventing tampering or contamination\n\n2. Collection procedures\n- Proper preservation techniques\n- Forensic protocols\n- Scientific methods for gathering evidence\n\n3. Storage requirements\n- Maintaining evidence in secure, controlled environments\n- Preventing degradation or loss of evidence\n- Temperature and humidity control\n\n4. Admissibility standards\n- Determining whether evidence meets legal standards\n- Ensuring evidence is relevant and reliable\n- Excluding improperly obtained or unreliable evidence\n\n5. Digital evidence regulations\n- Procedures for collecting electronic data\n- Maintaining digital evidence integrity\n- Preventing manipulation of digital records\n\n6. Privacy protections\n- Ensuring proper handling of sensitive information\n- Protecting individual rights during evidence collection\n- Compliance with constitutional requirements\n\nThese laws vary by jurisdiction and are crucial in maintaining fair and just legal proceedings.",
